{"title_page": "Uniform of The Royal High School, Edinburgh", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{details|Royal High School (Edinburgh)}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:RHS Captain.png|thumb|left|The Royal High School Full Colours]] -->\n\nThe school uniform is black and white, derived from the municipal colours of Edinburgh.<ref> [http://www.royalhigh.edin.sch.uk/content/information/history/index.htm The Royal High School: School History]. Retrieved on 2 September 2007.</ref>\n\nThe school retains the now traditional uniform of a blazer and tie. Boys are required to wear a plain white shirt, official tie, black blazer with school badge, black trousers and black polished leather school shoes.<ref>[https://royalhigh.wordpress.com/school-uniform The Royal High School: School Uniform]</ref> There is the option of a black pullover. Girls must wear a white blouse, official tie, black pullover or cardigan, black blazer with school badge, black skirt or trousers, black tights and black polished leather school shoes. A black and white striped tie is standard; a plain black tie denotes a Sixth Year.\n\nThe school badge features the school motto and the embattled triple-towered castle of the school arms. [[Prefect]]s and [[Vice Captains]] are presented with a silver badge whilst the [[School Captain]] is presented with a gold badge to pin on his or her blazer.  A select few 5th-formers are also awarded a [[Prefect]] badge.\n\nWhen full colours are awarded to a pupil a new pocket is attached to the blazer with the school emblem embroidered in silver wire with the dates of the present academic year either side of the badge.<ref>http://www.royalhigh.edin.sch.uk/content/information/prospectus/school.htm</ref>\n\nThese dress regulations, which were introduced to include those for girls as well as boys, date from 1973.<ref>Barclay, ''Tounis Scule'', p. 82, Appendix X: 'School Rules of Discipline', pp. 134-6.</ref>\n\nThe school garb worn at the end of the eighteenth century is described by [[Henry Cockburn, Lord Cockburn|Lord Cockburn]]:\n\n{{quote|It consisted of a round black hat; a shirt fastened at the neck by a black ribbon, and except on dress-days, unruffled; a cloth waistcoat, rather large, with two rows of buttons and of buttonholes, so that it could be buttoned on either side, which, when one side got dirty, was convenient; a single-breasted jacket, which in due time got a tail and became a coat; brown corduroy breeches, tied at the knees by a brown cotton tape; worsted stockings in winter, blue cotton stockings in summer, and white cotton for dress; clumsy shoes, made to be used on either foot, and each requiring to be used on alternative feet daily; brass or copper buckles.  The coat and waistcoat were always of glaring colours, such as bright blue, grass green, and scarlet.  I remember well the pride with which I was once rigged out in a scarlet waistcoat, and a bright green coat.<ref>Trotter, ''Royal High School'', pp. 123-4.</ref>}}\n\nClothing patterns were gradually standardised from the 1860s,<ref>Robert Anderson, 'Secondary Schools and Scottish Society in the Nineteenth Century', ''Past and Present'', No. 109 (November 1985), p. 195.</ref> and an outfitter, Aitken & Niven, was appointed for the school after 1905. The blazer became part of the regular uniform in the early 1930s. The school badge was introduced in 1921, superseding an intertwined monogram RHS in silver thread on a black school cap, which had been standard wear since the turn of the twentieth century. The cap became a casualty of the clothes rationing and wartime austerity of the 1940s, since when pupils have gone bareheaded.<ref>Barclay, ''Tounis Scule'', pp. 81, 82.</ref> Long trousers replaced shorts by the 1970s.\n\nLike the uniform, the school sports colours are black and white. They were adopted from the city in 1875. Prior to 1866 the sports colours were white with an orange scarf; between 1866 and 1869, white with a blue and orange scarf; between 1869 and 1871, blue and orange; and between 1871 and 1875, scarlet and blue.<ref>Barclay, ''Tounis Scule'', p. 82.</ref> This rapid [[Victorian era|mid-Victorian]] evolution was prompted by the innovation of annual games.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:British uniforms]]\n[[Category:Royal High School, Edinburgh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{details|Royal High School (Edinburgh)}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:RHS Captain.png|thumb|left|The Royal High School Full Colours]] -->\n\nThe school uniform is black and white, derived from the municipal colours of Edinburgh.<ref> [http://www.royalhigh.edin.sch.uk/content/information/history/index.htm The Royal High School: School History]. Retrieved on 2 September 2007.</ref>\n\nThe school retains the now traditional uniform of a blazer and tie. Boys are required to wear a plain white shirt, official tie, black blazer with school badge, black trousers and black polished leather school shoes.  There is the option of a black pullover.  Girls must wear a white blouse, official tie, black pullover or cardigan, black blazer with school badge, black skirt or trousers, black tights and black polished leather school shoes. A black and white striped tie is standard; a plain black tie denotes a Sixth Year.\n\nThe school badge features the school motto and the embattled triple-towered castle of the school arms. [[Prefect]]s and [[Vice Captains]] are presented with a silver badge whilst the [[School Captain]] is presented with a gold badge to pin on his or her blazer.  A select few 5th-formers are also awarded a [[Prefect]] badge.\n\nWhen full colours are awarded to a pupil a new pocket is attached to the blazer with the school emblem embroidered in silver wire with the dates of the present academic year either side of the badge.<ref>http://www.royalhigh.edin.sch.uk/content/information/prospectus/school.htm</ref>\n\nThese dress regulations, which were introduced to include those for girls as well as boys, date from 1973.<ref>Barclay, ''Tounis Scule'', p. 82, Appendix X: 'School Rules of Discipline', pp. 134-6.</ref>\n\nThe school garb worn at the end of the eighteenth century is described by [[Henry Cockburn, Lord Cockburn|Lord Cockburn]]:\n\n{{quote|It consisted of a round black hat; a shirt fastened at the neck by a black ribbon, and except on dress-days, unruffled; a cloth waistcoat, rather large, with two rows of buttons and of buttonholes, so that it could be buttoned on either side, which, when one side got dirty, was convenient; a single-breasted jacket, which in due time got a tail and became a coat; brown corduroy breeches, tied at the knees by a brown cotton tape; worsted stockings in winter, blue cotton stockings in summer, and white cotton for dress; clumsy shoes, made to be used on either foot, and each requiring to be used on alternative feet daily; brass or copper buckles.  The coat and waistcoat were always of glaring colours, such as bright blue, grass green, and scarlet.  I remember well the pride with which I was once rigged out in a scarlet waistcoat, and a bright green coat.<ref>Trotter, ''Royal High School'', pp. 123-4.</ref>}}\n\nClothing patterns were gradually standardised from the 1860s,<ref>Robert Anderson, 'Secondary Schools and Scottish Society in the Nineteenth Century', ''Past and Present'', No. 109 (November 1985), p. 195.</ref> and an outfitter, Aitken & Niven, was appointed for the school after 1905. The blazer became part of the regular uniform in the early 1930s. The school badge was introduced in 1921, superseding an intertwined monogram RHS in silver thread on a black school cap, which had been standard wear since the turn of the twentieth century. The cap became a casualty of the clothes rationing and wartime austerity of the 1940s, since when pupils have gone bareheaded.<ref>Barclay, ''Tounis Scule'', pp. 81, 82.</ref> Long trousers replaced shorts by the 1970s.\n\nLike the uniform, the school sports colours are black and white. They were adopted from the city in 1875. Prior to 1866 the sports colours were white with an orange scarf; between 1866 and 1869, white with a blue and orange scarf; between 1869 and 1871, blue and orange; and between 1871 and 1875, scarlet and blue.<ref>Barclay, ''Tounis Scule'', p. 82.</ref> This rapid [[Victorian era|mid-Victorian]] evolution was prompted by the innovation of annual games.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:British uniforms]]\n[[Category:Royal High School, Edinburgh]]\n", "name_user": "Johan Vonk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add reference (Official school website)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_of_The_Royal_High_School,_Edinburgh"}
{"title_page": "Granada Hills Charter High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Granada Hills Charter High School\n|motto          = Home of the Highlanders\n|image          = Granada-Hills-Charter-High-School.jpg\n|streetaddress  = 10535 Zelzah Avenue\n|city           = Los Angeles\n|state          = [[California]]\n|country        = USA\n|zipcode        = 91344\n|coordinates    = {{Coord|34.2611|-118.5254|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|imagesize      = 220px\n|established    = {{Start date and age|1960}}\n|type           = [[Charter school]]\n|affiliation    =\n|accreditation  = [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges|WASC]]<ref name=\"wasc\"/>\n|district       = [[Los Angeles Unified School District]]\n|grades         = [[ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]<ref name=\"nces_sch\" />\n|principal      = Brian Bauer\n|faculty        =\n|staff          =\n|students       =\n|enrollment     = 4,662 (2016\u201317){{NCES School ID|062271003050|school_name=Granada_Hills_Charter_High_School|access_date=May 10, 2019|do_not_render=y}}\n| teaching_staff = 171.87 ([[full-time equivalent|FTE]]) (2016\u201317)<ref name=\"nces_sch\" />\n| ratio         = {{Ratio|27.13|1}} (2016\u201317)<ref name=\"nces_sch\" />\n|athletics      = \n|conference     = [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[CIF Los Angeles City Section|Los Angeles]]<br>West Valley League\n|colors         = {{Color box|Green}} Green<br>{{Color box|Black}} Black<br>{{Color box|White}} White\n|mascot         = The Highlander\n|newspaper      = The Plaid Press\n|yearbook       = Tartan\n|information    =\n|website        = {{URL|www.ghchs.com}}\n}}\n'''Granada Hills Charter High School''' (often abbreviated to '''GHCHS''' or simply '''Granada''') is an independent charter school consisting of over 4,600 students in grades 9\u201312, located in the [[Granada Hills, Los Angeles|Granada Hills]] neighborhood of Los Angeles. It is the largest charter school in the nation. Granada also has a high Academic Performance Index (API) score of 878, greatly exceeding the target API score of 800 for all schools in California.<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://www.ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=150850&id=0 | title = Granada Hills Charter High School API Rockets to 874 | year = 2011 | publisher = Granada Hills Charter High School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711092058/http://www.ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=150850&id=0 | archivedate = July 11, 2011 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> On April 12, 2011, Granada was named a 2011 [[California Distinguished School]].<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://www.ghchs.com/academics/pressreleases/GHCHS%20Named%20CA%20Distinguished%20School%20-%20Press%20Release.pdf | title = Granada Hills Charter High School named California Distinguished School | year = 2011 | publisher = Granada Hills Charter High School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130509203843/http://www.ghchs.com/academics/pressreleases/GHCHS%20Named%20CA%20Distinguished%20School%20-%20Press%20Release.pdf | archivedate = May 9, 2013 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> On December 22, 2011, Granada became an [[International Baccalaureate World School]].<ref name=\"Granada Hills Charter High School\">{{cite press release | url = http://ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=231944&id=0 | title = GHCHS now an International Baccalaureate World School | year = 2011 | publisher = Granada Hills Charter High School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120312014836/http://www.ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=231944&id=0 | archivedate = March 12, 2012 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Since 2011, the school has won seven National [[Academic Decathlon]] Championships.\n\n==History==\nGranada Hills High School is a comprehensive public high school, founded in 1960.<ref name=\"About Us\">{{cite web |title=About Us - Miscellaneous - Granada Hills Charter High School |url=https://www.ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=854776&type=d&pREC_ID=1260787 |website=www.ghchs.com |accessdate=5 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Bryce Schurr was the first acting principal of the school.<ref>{{cite news |last1=LA |first1=Times |title=LA Times |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jun/05/local/me-57001}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970-71 and 1971-72 school years, Granada Hills High had the largest student body of any high school in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Hier | first = Jim | title = Granada Hills (Images of America) | publisher = [[Arcadia Publishing]] | date = 2007 | isbn = 0738547719 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5yKZhnxurSUC&pg=PA9 | page = 9}} 9780738547718</ref> The school was relieved by the 1971 opening of [[John F. Kennedy High School (Los Angeles)|John F. Kennedy High School]].<ref>{{Cite book | last = Hier | first = Jim | title = Granada Hills (Images of America) | publisher = [[Arcadia Publishing]] | date = 2007 | isbn = 0738547719 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5yKZhnxurSUC&pg=PA10 | page = 10}} 9780738547718</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the school opened a LAUSD [[magnet school]] with emphasis in math, science and technology in conjunction with the California State University at Northridge. In 2003, the school was awarded charter status which granted it fiscal and instructional autonomy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=99795&type=d&pREC_ID=191580 |title=Charter School FAQs |work=ghchs.com |publisher=Granada Hills Charter High School |accessdate=October 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711091723/http://ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=99795&type=d&pREC_ID=191580 |archivedate=July 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 the Los Angeles Board of Education voted to allow the school to become a charter, making it the largest school in the United States to convert to a charter school.<ref name=DiMassaLAcharter>DiMassa, Cara Mia. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/2003/may/14/local/me-lausd14 Granada Hills Gets Charter OK].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. May 14, 2003. Retrieved on January 8, 2016.</ref> The school administration asked for a charter status since being directly operated the district limited its fundraising opportunities, and it also was against LAUSD funding cuts.<ref>Corwin, Ronald G. and Joe Schneider. ''The School Choice Hoax: Fixing America's Schools''. [[Greenwood Publishing Group]], January 1, 2005. {{ISBN|0275986950}}, 9780275986957. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=2rQ8EnBEyqkC&pg=PA221 221].</ref>\n\nIn mid 2013, Granada Hills Charter High School purchased the nearby Pinecrest Northridge Elementary School campus for $5.6M,<ref>{{cite news |title=Granada Hills Charter High buys Pinecrest Northridge campus for $5.6M |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130408/granada-hills-charter-high-buys-pinecrest-northridge-campus-for-56m |work=Los Angeles Daily News |accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref> using funds obtained from the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]]. Granada Hills Charter High School used this new land to create iGranada, a campus specializing in digital arts and sciences. This campus opened for the first time for the Fall 2015 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url =http://www.ghchs.com/academic_programs/igranada/igranada_digital_arts_sciences/|title =IGRANADA DIGITAL ARTS & SCIENCES|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150927225848/http://www.ghchs.com/academic_programs/igranada/igranada_digital_arts_sciences/|archivedate =September 27, 2015|df =mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs part of their Charter Renewal Petition, GHCHS has applied to increase their enrollment from 4,300 students up to 5,500 students. This includes adding approximately 200 additional grades 9-12 seats to the existing GHCHS campus, through a Charter Augmentation Grant, and adding up to 1,000 additional seats at the Pinecrest site (or at another possible property acquisition).<ref>{{citation |title=Granada Hills Charter High School: A Charter School Petition for Renewal |url=http://laschoolboard.org/sites/default/files/Petition-Renewal-Granada-Hills-HS-02-11-14.pdf |accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Technology ==\nOn campus, there are six computer labs, each with more than 35 computers. There are also laptop carts, which house many laptop computers and can be transported around the campus for enrichment activities. Science classrooms are updated with new lab technology often. Most classrooms have [[Smart Board|Smart Boards]] and projectors, increasing the overall student interaction in class.\n\nBeginning in the 2015-2016 school year, [[Chromebook|Chromebooks]] are given to every student. Teachers may use [[Google Classroom]] to post assignments, online teaching materials, and give instant feedback to the students. Additionally, the school has wifi networks campuswide, and can provide wifi at a student's home if they cannot afford it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghchs.com/offices/technology|title=Technology - Granada Hills Charter High School|work=ghchs.com|accessdate=December 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227190934/http://ghchs.com/offices/technology/|archive-date=December 27, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\n==Demographics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[White Americans|White]] !! [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic/Latino]] !! [[Asian people|Asian]] !! [[African American]] !! [[Pacific Islander]] !! [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|American Indian]] !! [[Multiracial|Two or More Races]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 25% || 40% || 28% || 4% || 0.3% || 0.3% || 3%\n|}\n\nAccording to [[US News and World Report]], as of 2019, 75% of Granada's student body is \"minority,\" with 47% of the student body coming from an economically disadvantaged household, determined by student eligibility for California's [[Reduced-price meal]] program.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/california/districts/los-angeles-unified-school-district/granada-hills-charter-high-2542/student-body | title = Granada Hills Charter High Student Body | access-date = May 10, 2019 | work = [[US News and World Report]]}}</ref>\n\nThe school is accredited by the [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]].<ref name=\"wasc\">{{Cite web | url = http://directory.acswasc.org/ | title = Directory of Schools | website = Acswasc.org | publisher = Accrediting Commission for Schools Western Association of Schools and Colleges | access-date=January 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe school's sports stadium, the [[John Elway Stadium]], is used by the [[Los Angeles Rampage]] women's soccer team and is the former home ground of the [[San Fernando Valley Quakes]] [[United Soccer Leagues]] [[USL Premier Development League|Premier Development League]] soccer team.\n\n==Academics==\nGranada offers 29 [[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses and 38 IB courses which include: [[AP Biology]], [[AP Chemistry]], [[AP Physics 1]], [[AP Physics 2]], [[AP Physics C]], [[AP Environmental Science]], [[AP Computer Science A]], [[AP Computer Science Principles]], [[AP Statistics]], [[AP Calculus AB]], [[AP Calculus BC]], [[AP English Language]], [[AP English Literature]], [[AP European History]], [[AP World History]], [[AP United States History]], [[AP Psychology]], [[AP United States Government]], [[AP Macroeconomics]], [[AP Microeconomics]], [[AP Human Geography]], [[AP Art History]], [[AP Music Theory]], [[AP Studio Art]], [[AP Chinese Language and Culture]], [[AP French Language]], [[AP Spanish Language]], and [[AP Spanish Literature]]. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=867260&type=d&pREC_ID=1226475 | title = Advanced Placement (AP) | access-date = October 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\nGranada Hills Charter High School offers a wide variety of extra curricular activities which include, [[Associated Student Body]] (ASB), [[Dance Team]], [[Cheer]], [[Show Choir]], Honors Choir, [[Jazz Band]], [[Marching Band]] and [[Color Guard]], [[Winter Guard]], [[Indoor Percussion]], and [[Orchestra]]. With that, the school also offers several academic teams such as [[Academic Decathlon]], [[DECA (organization)|DECA]], [[Envirothon]], [[Robotics]], [[Model United Nations]], [[Science Bowl]], [[Science Olympiad]], and [[Speech and Debate]]. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=868937&type=d&pREC_ID=1227367 | title = Activities - Granada Hills Charter High School | access-date = October 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Academic Decathlon===\n\nThe [[Academic Decathlon]] team won back-to-back-to-back National championships in 2011, 2012 and 2013. The 2015 team also secured another national championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/granada-hills-charter-high-school-wins-third-national-academic-decathlon-205032191.html|title=Granada Hills H.S. Wins U.S. Academic Decathlon|work=nbclosangeles.com|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Granada also won again in 2016 and 2017 [[United States Academic Decathlon National Championship|National Academic Decathlon Championship]] for another back-to-back championship win, its sixth championship win so far. The 2019 team also captured another Academic Decathlon Championship title winning 7 title in a span of 9 years.\n\n===Model United Nations===\n\nThe nationally-ranked<ref> {{cite web | url = https://bestdelegate.com/the-top-150-high-school-model-united-nations-teams-in-north-america-from-the-2017-2018-school-year/ | title = The Top 150 High School Model United Nations Teams in North America from the 2017-2018 School Year | access-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> [[Model United Nations]] team at Granada Hills Charter has been recognized at various conferences across North America. During the 2017-2018 season, they won Best Small Delegation at Harvard Model UN (HMUN).<ref>{{cite web | url = https://allamericanmun.com/can-you-help-us-delegation-award-winners/ |title = Delegation Award Winners | access-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, GHC Model UN won the Award of Distinction at the National High School Model United Nations (NHSMUN).<ref> {{cite web | url = https://theplaidpress.com/2019/04/05/ghc-model-united-nations-takes-the-big-apple-by-storm/ | title = GHC Model United Nations takes the Big Apple by storm. | access-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> GHCMUN notably hosts the Valley Regional Model United Nations (VRMUN), the first high-school Model UN conference in the [[San Fernando Valley]].<ref> {{cite web | url = https://theplaidpress.com/2020/02/21/granada-hosts-first-valley-regional-mun-conference/ | title = Granada hosts first Valley Regional MUN conference | access-date = February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Speech & Debate===\n\nIn 2011, Granada Hills Charter won the Stanford Junior Varsity LD tournament<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://docs.google.com/a/snfi.org/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=c25maS5vcmd8MjAxMS1zdGFuZm9yZC1pbnZpdGF0aW9uYWwtcmVzdWx0c3xneDo3NzRmZjI5NGEzZmE3YmM2 | title = 2011 Standford Invitational | access-date = May 10, 2019}}</ref> (Yellow River)It was also the 2008 [[CHSSA]] State Champion in [[Thematic Interpretation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CHHSA State Results For Members of the TVFL|url=http://welcome.to/tvfl|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082847/http://welcome.to/tvfl|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 4, 2016|accessdate=July 21, 2008}} </ref> In 2011 took 13th at the CHSSA State tournament in Original Prose and Poetry\n\n===Marching Band & Color Guard===\n\nIn 2012, the Granada Hills Charter High School Marching Band was awarded a bronze medal at the 2012 [[SCSBOA]] Division 5A Field Show Championships. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.worldofpageantry.com/scores/fall12-scores.php | title = World of Pageantry - Fall 2012 Western States High School Band Results & Scores | access-date = October 13, 2019}}</ref> In 2016, the Highlander Band participated in the 2016 [[Bands of America]] St. George Regional Championships in [[St. George, Utah]] and was awarded and recognized as an [[SCSBOA]] 4A Finalist that year. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.worldofpageantry.com/scores/fall16-scores.php| title = World of Pageantry - Fall 2016 Western States High School Band Results & Scores | access-date = December 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n\n\n===Baseball===\n\n[[Ryan Braun]] was a four-year [[Letterman (sports)|letterman]] on the Granada Hills High School baseball team, and three-year team captain and Most Valuable Player (MVP). In 2002, he batted .451 as a senior, with an [[On-base percentage|OBP]] of .675, and broke the school record for career [[home runs]] with 25.<ref>Mulhern, Tom, \"Brewers: Braun's start a smashing success\", ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'', July 21, 2007. Retrieved December 20, 2007.</ref>\n\n===Basketball===\n\nIn 1964, Granada Hills High School won the L.A. City Basketball Championship.\n\nIn 2019, the Granada Hills Charter High School Boys Basketball team won the Division I Los Angeles City Section Championship defeating [[University High School (Los Angeles)|University High School]] 71-54 to win their first City title since 1987.\n\n===Cross Country===\n\nThe Boys and Girls Cross Country Teams gained prominence in the mid to late 2010s competing in Los Angeles City Section.\n\nIn 2013 the Girls Team placed 2nd in the Division I Los Angeles City Section Cross Country Finals. Placing 2nd also ensured their first ever appearance in the CIF State Cross Country Championships.\n\nIn 2016 both teams advanced to the CIF State Cross Country Championships after they each placed 2nd in their races in the Division I Los Angeles City Section Cross Country Finals. The placement also marked the Boys Team's first appearance in the CIF State Cross Country Championships.\n\nIn 2017 the Girls Team won their first Los Angeles City Section title by winning the Division I race with a score of 53 points. They later went on to place 13th at the CIF State Cross Country Championships in Division I. The following year in 2018 they repeated as Division I Los Angeles City Section Champions in with 43 points. The victory also ensured a 3rd consecutive trip to the CIF State Cross Country Championships. For the third straight year in 2019, the girls Cross Country team won the Division I City Title this time with 30 points.\n\nIn 2018 the Boys Team won the Los Angeles City Section Cross Country Finals Division I race with a score of 53 points. It was their 2nd trip to the CIF State Cross Country Championships in 3 years, but most importantly the victory ended a 42 year long title drought of winning a City Championship, which hasn't happened since 1976.\n\n===Football===\n\nIn 1970, Granada Hills High School won the L.A. City Football Championship with the five-receiver passing attack innovated by Coach [[Jack Neumeier]] later known as the [[spread offense]] that a few years later attracted [[John Elway]]'s father, [[Jack Elway]]'s attention, after the Elway family moved to Los Angeles when Jack Elway assumed the head football coaching position at California State University, Northridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/sep/03/local/me-neumeier3|title=Jack Neumeier, 85; High School Football Coach Inspired Elway |accessdate=October 10, 2012 | newspaper=The Los Angeles Times |first=Eric |last=Sondheimer |date=September 3, 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, in a highly publicized rematch, Granada Hills High School upset the Carson Colts (at the time the #2 rated high school football team in the United States), 27-14, to win their second L.A. City Football Championship. Head coach Darryl Stroh, offensive coordinator Tom Harp, and line coach Bill Lake were instrumental in developing a successful new game plan that countered Carson's offensive juggernaut and ferocious pass rush. Carson had clobbered Granada, 42-14, earlier in the season. It is still regarded as one of the biggest upsets in the history of L.A. high school football.\n\n===Soccer===\nIn 2017, both the Boys and Girls soccer teams won the Division I LA City Championship. \n\nIn 2019, the Girls won another LA City Championship defeating league rival [[El Camino Real Charter High School|El Camino Real]] in a penalty shootout.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{refimprove|section|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Rbraunmil2014.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Ryan Braun]]]]\n[[File:Uso-show-john-elway-defenselink-mil.jpg|thumb|180px|[[John Elway]]]]\n* [[Cameron Lynn|Ariane Andrew]], professional wrestler and singer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article34323681.html|title=WWE Diva Cameron starts right cause with \u2018Wrong #\u2019|website=[[The Miami Herald]]|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 15, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[James Bacon (political aide)|James Bacon]], Director of Operations of the White House Office of Presidential Personnel<ref>https://www.insider.com/james-bacon-college-senior-white-house-official-history-2020-2</ref> \n* [[Doug Baker (baseball)|Doug Baker]], professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/high-schools/granada-hills-1725.shtml |title=Granada Hills: High School Alumni |accessdate=August 29, 2007 |work=The Baseball Cube |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821144457/http://www.thebaseballcube.com/high-schools/granada-hills-1725.shtml |archivedate=August 21, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Dave Baldwin (American football)|Dave Baldwin]], college football coach<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csurams.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/baldwin_dave00.html |title=Colorado State Football}}</ref>\n* [[Valerie Bertinelli]], actress<ref>{{cite web|title=Vacations in California travel Guide|url=http://www.seecalifornia.com/things-to-do/granada-hills.html|website=things-to-do granada-hillsl|accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Justine Biticon]], model\n* [[Ryan Braun]] (born 1983), major league baseball All Star player for Milwaukee Brewers, 2011 MVP<ref name=baseballcube/>\n* [[Jamal Brooks]], professional football player<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Brooks Stats |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BrooJa20.htm |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=11 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Budaska]], professional baseball player and coach\n* [[Bill Buford]], author/writer\n* [[Bryan Caplan]], economist, [[natalist]], teacher\n* [[John Elway]] (born 1960), Hall of Fame  quarterback for the [[Denver Broncos]]; the [[John Elway Stadium|school's stadium]] was later named after him\n* [[Robert Englund]], actor best known for playing the infamous [[serial killer]] [[Freddy Krueger]] in the [[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|''Nightmare on Elm Street'' film series]]\n* [[Dave Fogel]], Radio/TV star\n* [[Gary Frank (actor)|Gary Frank]], actor and director\n*[[Jo Freeman]] (born 1945), feminist, political scientist, writer, and attorney\n* [[Brad Garfield]], television director{{citation needed|reason=linked article lacks a source to support alumnus status|date=July 2018}}\n* [[Bob Hite]], musician\n* [[Travis Kalanick]], co-founder of [[Uber]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Travis Kalanick |url=https://www.nndb.com/people/603/000396412/ |website=nndb.com |accessdate=13 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Barry Kerzin]], professor of medicine and Buddhist monk<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ghdonline.org/users/barry-kerzin/ | publisher=GHDonline | title=Barry Kerzin, About | accessdate=March 30, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Kameron Loe]], professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube/>\n*[[Hana Mae Lee]], comedian and actress<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://charactermedia.com/october-issue-pitch-perfect-actress-hana-mae-lee-makes-her-big-screen-debut/|title=October Issue: \u2018Pitch Perfect\u2019 Actress Hana Mae Lee Makes Her Big Screen Debut|last=Media|first=Character|date=2012-10-10|website=Character Media|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n* [[John Lee (California politician)|John Lee]], member of [[Los Angeles City Council]]\n* [[Geoffrey Marcy]], UC Berkeley astronomy professor, discoverer of planets \n* [[Gary Matthews, Jr.]] (born 1974), professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube/>\n* [[Blanchard Montgomery]], professional football player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MONTGBLA01 |title=Blanchard Montgomery |accessdate=August 29, 2007 |work=DatabaseFootball.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929231341/http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MONTGBLA01 |archivedate=September 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Michael Morhaime]], videogame producer and cofounder of Blizzard Entertainment<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Granada_Hills_High_School_Tartan_Yearbook/1985/Page_130.html |title=Granada Hills High School Tartan Yearbook |page=130}}</ref>\n* [[Neal Morse]], progressive rock musician\n* [[Jeffrey Lee Pierce]], guitarist of [[The Gun Club]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Biography |url=http://www.jeffreyleepierce.com/Site/Biography.html |website=www.jeffreyleepierce.com |accessdate=15 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Kristine Quance]], swimming Olympic gold medalist 1996\n* [[Dave Schmidt]], professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube/>\n* [[Alex Solowitz]], actor <ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0813565/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1]</ref>\n* [[Tamlyn Tomita]], actress best known for starring in ''[[The Good Doctor (TV series)|The Good Doctor]]'' and ''[[The Karate Kid Part II]]''\n* [[Lisa Wilhoit]], actress<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile on ''Metacritic'' |url=https://www.metacritic.com/person/lisa-wilhoit |website=www.metacritic.com |accessdate=2 December 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Curtis Williams]], actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110711093003/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202004%20-%202009.pdf Charter petition 2004-2009] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6eNjOWtPk?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20110711093003/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202004%20-%202009.pdf Archive])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110711092613/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202009%20-%202014.pdf Charter petition 2009-2014] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6eNjXBdY7?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20110711092613/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202009%20-%202014.pdf Archive])\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Granada Hills, Los Angeles}}\n{{San Fernando Valley Schools}}\n{{LAUSD}}\n{{Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Los Angeles Unified School District schools]]\n[[Category:Granada Hills, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:High schools in the San Fernando Valley]]\n[[Category:High schools in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Charter high schools in California]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Cal State Northridge Matadors men's basketball]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name           = Granada Hills Charter High School\n|motto          = Home of the Highlanders\n|image          = Granada-Hills-Charter-High-School.jpg\n|streetaddress  = 10535 Zelzah Avenue\n|city           = Los Angeles\n|state          = [[California]]\n|country        = USA\n|zipcode        = 91344\n|coordinates    = {{Coord|34.2611|-118.5254|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|imagesize      = 220px\n|established    = {{Start date and age|1960}}\n|type           = [[Charter school]]\n|affiliation    =\n|accreditation  = [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges|WASC]]<ref name=\"wasc\"/>\n|district       = [[Los Angeles Unified School District]]\n|grades         = [[ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]<ref name=\"nces_sch\" />\n|principal      = Brian Bauer\n|faculty        =\n|staff          =\n|students       =\n|enrollment     = 4,662 (2016\u201317){{NCES School ID|062271003050|school_name=Granada_Hills_Charter_High_School|access_date=May 10, 2019|do_not_render=y}}\n| teaching_staff = 171.87 ([[full-time equivalent|FTE]]) (2016\u201317)<ref name=\"nces_sch\" />\n| ratio         = {{Ratio|27.13|1}} (2016\u201317)<ref name=\"nces_sch\" />\n|athletics      = \n|conference     = [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[CIF Los Angeles City Section|Los Angeles]]<br>West Valley League\n|colors         = {{Color box|Green}} Green<br>{{Color box|Black}} Black<br>{{Color box|White}} White\n|mascot         = The Highlander\n|newspaper      = The Plaid Press\n|yearbook       = Tartan\n|information    =\n|website        = {{URL|www.ghchs.com}}\n}}\n'''Granada Hills Charter High School''' (often abbreviated to '''GHCHS''' or simply '''Granada''') is an independent charter school consisting of over 4,600 students in grades 9\u201312, located in the [[Granada Hills, Los Angeles|Granada Hills]] neighborhood of Los Angeles. It is the largest charter school in the nation. Granada also has a high Academic Performance Index (API) score of 878, greatly exceeding the target API score of 800 for all schools in California.<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://www.ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=150850&id=0 | title = Granada Hills Charter High School API Rockets to 874 | year = 2011 | publisher = Granada Hills Charter High School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711092058/http://www.ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=150850&id=0 | archivedate = July 11, 2011 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> On April 12, 2011, Granada was named a 2011 [[California Distinguished School]].<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://www.ghchs.com/academics/pressreleases/GHCHS%20Named%20CA%20Distinguished%20School%20-%20Press%20Release.pdf | title = Granada Hills Charter High School named California Distinguished School | year = 2011 | publisher = Granada Hills Charter High School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130509203843/http://www.ghchs.com/academics/pressreleases/GHCHS%20Named%20CA%20Distinguished%20School%20-%20Press%20Release.pdf | archivedate = May 9, 2013 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> On December 22, 2011, Granada became an [[International Baccalaureate World School]].<ref name=\"Granada Hills Charter High School\">{{cite press release | url = http://ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=231944&id=0 | title = GHCHS now an International Baccalaureate World School | year = 2011 | publisher = Granada Hills Charter High School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120312014836/http://www.ghchs.com/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=231944&id=0 | archivedate = March 12, 2012 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Since 2011, the school has won seven National [[Academic Decathlon]] Championships.\n\n==History==\nGranada Hills High School is a comprehensive public high school, founded in 1960.<ref name=\"About Us\">{{cite web |title=About Us - Miscellaneous - Granada Hills Charter High School |url=https://www.ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=854776&type=d&pREC_ID=1260787 |website=www.ghchs.com |accessdate=5 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Bryce Schurr was the first acting principal of the school.<ref>{{cite news |last1=LA |first1=Times |title=LA Times |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jun/05/local/me-57001}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970-1971 and 1971-72 school years, Granada Hills High had the largest student body of any high school in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Hier | first = Jim | title = Granada Hills (Images of America) | publisher = [[Arcadia Publishing]] | date = 2007 | isbn = 0738547719 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5yKZhnxurSUC&pg=PA9 | page = 9}} 9780738547718</ref> The school was relieved by the 1971 opening of [[Kennedy High School (Los Angeles)|Kennedy High School]].<ref>{{Cite book | last = Hier | first = Jim | title = Granada Hills (Images of America) | publisher = [[Arcadia Publishing]] | date = 2007 | isbn = 0738547719 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5yKZhnxurSUC&pg=PA10 | page = 10}} 9780738547718</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the school opened a LAUSD [[magnet school]] with emphasis in math, science and technology in conjunction with the California State University at Northridge. In 2003, the school was awarded charter status which granted it fiscal and instructional autonomy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=99795&type=d&pREC_ID=191580 |title=Charter School FAQs |work=ghchs.com |publisher=Granada Hills Charter High School |accessdate=October 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711091723/http://ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=99795&type=d&pREC_ID=191580 |archivedate=July 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 the Los Angeles Board of Education voted to allow the school to become a charter, making it the largest school in the United States to convert to a charter school.<ref name=DiMassaLAcharter>DiMassa, Cara Mia. \"[http://articles.latimes.com/2003/may/14/local/me-lausd14 Granada Hills Gets Charter OK].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. May 14, 2003. Retrieved on January 8, 2016.</ref> The school administration asked for a charter status since being directly operated the district limited its fundraising opportunities, and it also was against LAUSD funding cuts.<ref>Corwin, Ronald G. and Joe Schneider. ''The School Choice Hoax: Fixing America's Schools''. [[Greenwood Publishing Group]], January 1, 2005. {{ISBN|0275986950}}, 9780275986957. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=2rQ8EnBEyqkC&pg=PA221 221].</ref>\n\nIn mid 2013, Granada Hills Charter High School purchased the nearby Pinecrest Northridge Elementary School campus for $5.6M,<ref>{{cite news |title=Granada Hills Charter High buys Pinecrest Northridge campus for $5.6M |url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20130408/granada-hills-charter-high-buys-pinecrest-northridge-campus-for-56m |work=Los Angeles Daily News |accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref> using funds obtained from the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]]. Granada Hills Charter High School used this new land to create iGranada, a campus specializing in digital arts and sciences. This campus opened for the first time for the Fall 2015 school year.<ref>{{Cite web|url =http://www.ghchs.com/academic_programs/igranada/igranada_digital_arts_sciences/|title =IGRANADA DIGITAL ARTS & SCIENCES|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150927225848/http://www.ghchs.com/academic_programs/igranada/igranada_digital_arts_sciences/|archivedate =September 27, 2015|df =mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs part of their Charter Renewal Petition, GHCHS has applied to increase their enrollment from 4,300 students up to 5,500 students. This includes adding approximately 200 additional grades 9-12 seats to the existing GHCHS campus, through a Charter Augmentation Grant, and adding up to 1,000 additional seats at the Pinecrest site (or at another possible property acquisition).<ref>{{citation |title=Granada Hills Charter High School: A Charter School Petition for Renewal |url=http://laschoolboard.org/sites/default/files/Petition-Renewal-Granada-Hills-HS-02-11-14.pdf |accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Technology ==\nOn campus, there are six computer labs, each with more than 35 computers. There are also laptop carts, which house many laptop computers and can be transported around the campus for enrichment activities. Science classrooms are updated with new lab technology often. Most classrooms have [[Smart Board|Smart Boards]] and projectors, increasing the overall student interaction in class.\n\nBeginning in the 2015-2016 school year, [[Chromebook|Chromebooks]] are given to every student. Teachers may use [[Google Classroom]] to post assignments, online teaching materials, and give instant feedback to the students. Additionally, the school has wifi networks campuswide, and can provide wifi at a student's home if they cannot afford it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghchs.com/offices/technology|title=Technology - Granada Hills Charter High School|work=ghchs.com|accessdate=December 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227190934/http://ghchs.com/offices/technology/|archive-date=December 27, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\n==Demographics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[White Americans|White]] !! [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic/Latino]] !! [[Asian people|Asian]] !! [[African American]] !! [[Pacific Islander]] !! [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|American Indian]] !! [[Multiracial|Two or More Races]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 25% || 40% || 28% || 4% || 0.3% || 0.3% || 3%\n|}\n\nAccording to [[US News and World Report]], as of 2019, 75% of Granada's student body is \"minority,\" with 47% of the student body coming from an economically disadvantaged household, determined by student eligibility for California's [[Reduced-price meal]] program.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/california/districts/los-angeles-unified-school-district/granada-hills-charter-high-2542/student-body | title = Granada Hills Charter High Student Body | access-date = May 10, 2019 | work = [[US News and World Report]]}}</ref>\n\nThe school is accredited by the [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]].<ref name=\"wasc\">{{Cite web | url = http://directory.acswasc.org/ | title = Directory of Schools | website = Acswasc.org | publisher = Accrediting Commission for Schools Western Association of Schools and Colleges | access-date=January 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe school's sports stadium, the [[John Elway Stadium]], is used by the [[Los Angeles Rampage]] women's soccer team and is the former home ground of the [[San Fernando Valley Quakes]] [[United Soccer Leagues]] [[USL Premier Development League|Premier Development League]] soccer team.\n\n==Academics==\nGranada offers 29 [[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses and 38 IB courses which include: [[AP Biology]], [[AP Chemistry]], [[AP Physics 1]], [[AP Physics 2]], [[AP Physics C]], [[AP Environmental Science]], [[AP Computer Science A]], [[AP Computer Science Principles]], [[AP Statistics]], [[AP Calculus AB]], [[AP Calculus BC]], [[AP English Language]], [[AP English Literature]], [[AP European History]], [[AP World History]], [[AP United States History]], [[AP Psychology]], [[AP United States Government]], [[AP Macroeconomics]], [[AP Microeconomics]], [[AP Human Geography]], [[AP Art History]], [[AP Music Theory]], [[AP Studio Art]], [[AP Chinese Language and Culture]], [[AP French Language]], [[AP Spanish Language]], and [[AP Spanish Literature]]. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=867260&type=d&pREC_ID=1226475 | title = Advanced Placement (AP) | access-date = October 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\nGranada Hills Charter High School offers a wide variety of extra curricular activities which include, [[Associated Student Body]] (ASB), [[Dance Team]], [[Cheer]], [[Show Choir]], Honors Choir, [[Jazz Band]], [[Marching Band]] and [[Color Guard]], [[Winter Guard]], [[Indoor Percussion]], and [[Orchestra]]. With that, the school also offers several academic teams such as [[Academic Decathlon]], [[DECA (organization)|DECA]], [[Envirothon]], [[Robotics]], [[Model United Nations]], [[Science Bowl]], [[Science Olympiad]], and [[Speech and Debate]]. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.ghchs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=868937&type=d&pREC_ID=1227367 | title = Activities - Granada Hills Charter High School | access-date = October 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Academic Decathlon===\n\nThe [[Academic Decathlon]] team won back-to-back-to-back National championships in 2011, 2012 and 2013. The 2015 team also secured another national championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/granada-hills-charter-high-school-wins-third-national-academic-decathlon-205032191.html|title=Granada Hills H.S. Wins U.S. Academic Decathlon|work=nbclosangeles.com|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Granada also won again in 2016 and 2017 [[United States Academic Decathlon National Championship|National Academic Decathlon Championship]] for another back-to-back championship win, its sixth championship win so far. The 2019 team also captured another Academic Decathlon Championship title winning 7 title in a span of 9 years.\n\n===Model United Nations===\n\nThe nationally-ranked<ref> {{cite web | url = https://bestdelegate.com/the-top-150-high-school-model-united-nations-teams-in-north-america-from-the-2017-2018-school-year/ | title = The Top 150 High School Model United Nations Teams in North America from the 2017-2018 School Year | access-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> [[Model United Nations]] team at Granada Hills Charter has been recognized at various conferences across North America. During the 2017-2018 season, they won Best Small Delegation at Harvard Model UN (HMUN).<ref>{{cite web | url = https://allamericanmun.com/can-you-help-us-delegation-award-winners/ |title = Delegation Award Winners | access-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, GHC Model UN won the Award of Distinction at the National High School Model United Nations (NHSMUN).<ref> {{cite web | url = https://theplaidpress.com/2019/04/05/ghc-model-united-nations-takes-the-big-apple-by-storm/ | title = GHC Model United Nations takes the Big Apple by storm. | access-date = December 6, 2019}}</ref> GHCMUN notably hosts the Valley Regional Model United Nations (VRMUN), the first high-school Model UN conference in the [[San Fernando Valley]].<ref> {{cite web | url = https://theplaidpress.com/2020/02/21/granada-hosts-first-valley-regional-mun-conference/ | title = Granada hosts first Valley Regional MUN conference | access-date = February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Speech & Debate===\n\nIn 2011, Granada Hills Charter won the Stanford Junior Varsity LD tournament<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://docs.google.com/a/snfi.org/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=c25maS5vcmd8MjAxMS1zdGFuZm9yZC1pbnZpdGF0aW9uYWwtcmVzdWx0c3xneDo3NzRmZjI5NGEzZmE3YmM2 | title = 2011 Standford Invitational | access-date = May 10, 2019}}</ref> (Yellow River)It was also the 2008 [[CHSSA]] State Champion in [[Thematic Interpretation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CHHSA State Results For Members of the TVFL|url=http://welcome.to/tvfl|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304082847/http://welcome.to/tvfl|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 4, 2016|accessdate=July 21, 2008}} </ref> In 2011 took 13th at the CHSSA State tournament in Original Prose and Poetry\n\n===Marching Band & Color Guard===\n\nIn 2012, the Granada Hills Charter High School Marching Band was awarded a bronze medal at the 2012 [[SCSBOA]] Division 5A Field Show Championships. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.worldofpageantry.com/scores/fall12-scores.php | title = World of Pageantry - Fall 2012 Western States High School Band Results & Scores | access-date = October 13, 2019}}</ref> In 2016, the Highlander Band participated in the 2016 [[Bands of America]] St. George Regional Championships in [[St. George, Utah]] and was awarded and recognized as an [[SCSBOA]] 4A Finalist that year. <ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.worldofpageantry.com/scores/fall16-scores.php| title = World of Pageantry - Fall 2016 Western States High School Band Results & Scores | access-date = December 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n\n\n===Baseball===\n\n[[Ryan Braun]] was a four-year [[Letterman (sports)|letterman]] on the Granada Hills High School baseball team, and three-year team captain and Most Valuable Player (MVP). In 2002, he batted .451 as a senior, with an [[On-base percentage|OBP]] of .675, and broke the school record for career [[home runs]] with 25.<ref>Mulhern, Tom, \"Brewers: Braun's start a smashing success\", ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'', July 21, 2007. Retrieved December 20, 2007.</ref>\n\n===Basketball===\n\nIn 1964, Granada Hills High School won the L.A. City Basketball Championship.\n\nIn 2019, the Granada Hills Charter High School Boys Basketball team won the Division I Los Angeles City Section Championship defeating [[University High School (Los Angeles)|University High School]] 71-54 to win their first City title since 1987.\n\n===Cross Country===\n\nThe Boys and Girls Cross Country Teams gained prominence in the mid to late 2010s competing in Los Angeles City Section.\n\nIn 2013 the Girls Team placed 2nd in the Division I Los Angeles City Section Cross Country Finals. Placing 2nd also ensured their first ever appearance in the CIF State Cross Country Championships.\n\nIn 2016 both teams advanced to the CIF State Cross Country Championships after they each placed 2nd in their races in the Division I Los Angeles City Section Cross Country Finals. The placement also marked the Boys Team's first appearance in the CIF State Cross Country Championships.\n\nIn 2017 the Girls Team won their first Los Angeles City Section title by winning the Division I race with a score of 53 points. They later went on to place 13th at the CIF State Cross Country Championships in Division I. The following year in 2018 they repeated as Division I Los Angeles City Section Champions in with 43 points. The victory also ensured a 3rd consecutive trip to the CIF State Cross Country Championships. For the third straight year in 2019, the girls Cross Country team won the Division I City Title this time with 30 points.\n\nIn 2018 the Boys Team won the Los Angeles City Section Cross Country Finals Division I race with a score of 53 points. It was their 2nd trip to the CIF State Cross Country Championships in 3 years, but most importantly the victory ended a 42 year long title drought of winning a City Championship, which hasn't happened since 1976.\n\n===Football===\n\nIn 1970, Granada Hills High School won the L.A. City Football Championship with the five-receiver passing attack innovated by Coach [[Jack Neumeier]] later known as the [[spread offense]] that a few years later attracted [[John Elway]]'s father, [[Jack Elway]]'s attention, after the Elway family moved to Los Angeles when Jack Elway assumed the head football coaching position at California State University, Northridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/sep/03/local/me-neumeier3|title=Jack Neumeier, 85; High School Football Coach Inspired Elway |accessdate=October 10, 2012 | newspaper=The Los Angeles Times |first=Eric |last=Sondheimer |date=September 3, 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, in a highly publicized rematch, Granada Hills High School upset the Carson Colts (at the time the #2 rated high school football team in the United States), 27-14, to win their second L.A. City Football Championship. Head coach Darryl Stroh, offensive coordinator Tom Harp, and line coach Bill Lake were instrumental in developing a successful new game plan that countered Carson's offensive juggernaut and ferocious pass rush. Carson had clobbered Granada, 42-14, earlier in the season. It is still regarded as one of the biggest upsets in the history of L.A. high school football.\n\n===Soccer===\nIn 2017, both the Boys and Girls soccer teams won the Division I LA City Championship. \n\nIn 2019, the Girls won another LA City Championship defeating league rival [[El Camino Real Charter High School|El Camino Real]] in a penalty shootout.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{refimprove|section|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Rbraunmil2014.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Ryan Braun]]]]\n[[File:Uso-show-john-elway-defenselink-mil.jpg|thumb|180px|[[John Elway]]]]\n* [[Cameron Lynn|Ariane Andrew]], professional wrestler and singer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article34323681.html|title=WWE Diva Cameron starts right cause with \u2018Wrong #\u2019|website=[[The Miami Herald]]|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 15, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[James Bacon (political aide)|James Bacon]], Director of Operations of the White House Office of Presidential Personnel<ref>https://www.insider.com/james-bacon-college-senior-white-house-official-history-2020-2</ref> \n* [[Doug Baker (baseball)|Doug Baker]], professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/high-schools/granada-hills-1725.shtml |title=Granada Hills: High School Alumni |accessdate=August 29, 2007 |work=The Baseball Cube |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821144457/http://www.thebaseballcube.com/high-schools/granada-hills-1725.shtml |archivedate=August 21, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Dave Baldwin (American football)|Dave Baldwin]], college football coach<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csurams.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/baldwin_dave00.html |title=Colorado State Football}}</ref>\n* [[Valerie Bertinelli]], actress<ref>{{cite web|title=Vacations in California travel Guide|url=http://www.seecalifornia.com/things-to-do/granada-hills.html|website=things-to-do granada-hillsl|accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Justine Biticon]], model\n* [[Ryan Braun]] (born 1983), major league baseball All Star player for Milwaukee Brewers, 2011 MVP<ref name=baseballcube/>\n* [[Jamal Brooks]], professional football player<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Brooks Stats |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BrooJa20.htm |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=11 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Budaska]], professional baseball player and coach\n* [[Bill Buford]], author/writer\n* [[Bryan Caplan]], economist, [[natalist]], teacher\n* [[John Elway]] (born 1960), Hall of Fame  quarterback for the [[Denver Broncos]]; the [[John Elway Stadium|school's stadium]] was later named after him\n* [[Robert Englund]], actor best known for playing the infamous [[serial killer]] [[Freddy Krueger]] in the [[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|''Nightmare on Elm Street'' film series]]\n* [[Dave Fogel]], Radio/TV star\n* [[Gary Frank (actor)|Gary Frank]], actor and director\n*[[Jo Freeman]] (born 1945), feminist, political scientist, writer, and attorney\n* [[Brad Garfield]], television director{{citation needed|reason=linked article lacks a source to support alumnus status|date=July 2018}}\n* [[Bob Hite]], musician\n* [[Travis Kalanick]], co-founder of [[Uber]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Travis Kalanick |url=https://www.nndb.com/people/603/000396412/ |website=nndb.com |accessdate=13 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Barry Kerzin]], professor of medicine and Buddhist monk<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ghdonline.org/users/barry-kerzin/ | publisher=GHDonline | title=Barry Kerzin, About | accessdate=March 30, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Kameron Loe]], professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube/>\n*[[Hana Mae Lee]], comedian and actress<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://charactermedia.com/october-issue-pitch-perfect-actress-hana-mae-lee-makes-her-big-screen-debut/|title=October Issue: \u2018Pitch Perfect\u2019 Actress Hana Mae Lee Makes Her Big Screen Debut|last=Media|first=Character|date=2012-10-10|website=Character Media|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n* [[John Lee (California politician)|John Lee]], member of [[Los Angeles City Council]]\n* [[Geoffrey Marcy]], UC Berkeley astronomy professor, discoverer of planets \n* [[Gary Matthews, Jr.]] (born 1974), professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube/>\n* [[Blanchard Montgomery]], professional football player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MONTGBLA01 |title=Blanchard Montgomery |accessdate=August 29, 2007 |work=DatabaseFootball.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929231341/http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MONTGBLA01 |archivedate=September 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Michael Morhaime]], videogame producer and cofounder of Blizzard Entertainment<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Granada_Hills_High_School_Tartan_Yearbook/1985/Page_130.html |title=Granada Hills High School Tartan Yearbook |page=130}}</ref>\n* [[Neal Morse]], progressive rock musician\n* [[Jeffrey Lee Pierce]], guitarist of [[The Gun Club]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Biography |url=http://www.jeffreyleepierce.com/Site/Biography.html |website=www.jeffreyleepierce.com |accessdate=15 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Kristine Quance]], swimming Olympic gold medalist 1996\n* [[Dave Schmidt]], professional baseball player<ref name=baseballcube/>\n* [[Alex Solowitz]], actor <ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0813565/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1]</ref>\n* [[Tamlyn Tomita]], actress best known for starring in ''[[The Good Doctor (TV series)|The Good Doctor]]'' and ''[[The Karate Kid Part II]]''\n* [[Lisa Wilhoit]], actress<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile on ''Metacritic'' |url=https://www.metacritic.com/person/lisa-wilhoit |website=www.metacritic.com |accessdate=2 December 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Curtis Williams]], actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110711093003/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202004%20-%202009.pdf Charter petition 2004-2009] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6eNjOWtPk?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20110711093003/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202004%20-%202009.pdf Archive])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110711092613/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202009%20-%202014.pdf Charter petition 2009-2014] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6eNjXBdY7?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20110711092613/http://ghchs.com/ourpages/auto/2010/9/8/63697403/GHCHS%20Charter%20Petition%202009%20-%202014.pdf Archive])\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Granada Hills, Los Angeles}}\n{{San Fernando Valley Schools}}\n{{LAU